  title: Introduction
  textDataArray:
  - "<size=45>C# Data Types\r</size>\nAs explained in the variables chapter, a variable
    in C# must be a specified data type:\n\n<size=45>Example</size>\r\n<#538C51>int</color>
    myNum = <#F2B84B>5</color>; <#D95E32>// Integer (whole number)</color>\n<#538C51>double</color>
    myDoubleNum = <#F2B84B>5.99D</color>; <#D95E32>// Floating point number</color>\n<#538C51>char</color>
    myLetter = <#F2B84B>'D'</color>;  <#D95E32>// Character</color>\n<#538C51>bool</color>
    myBool = <#F2B84B>true</color>;  <#D95E32>// Boolean</color>\n<#538C51>string</color>
    myText = <#F2B84B>\"Hello\"</color>; <#D95E32>// String </color>\n"
  - 'A data type specifies the size and type of variable values.

    

    It
    is important to use the correct data type for the corresponding variable; to
    avoid errors, to save time and memory, but it will also make your code more maintainable
    and readable. The most common data types are:


    <#F2B84B>Data Type</color>:
    int

    <#F2B84B>Size: </color> 4 bytes

    <#F2B84B>Description:</color> Stores
    whole numbers from -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647'
  - '<#F2B84B>Data Type</color>: double

    <#F2B84B>Size: </color> 8 bytes

    <#F2B84B>Description:</color>
    Stores fractional numbers. Sufficient for storing 15 decimal digits'
  - '<#F2B84B>Data Type</color>: string

    <#F2B84B>Size: </color> 2 bytes per
    character

    <#F2B84B>Description:</color> Stores a sequence of characters,
    surrounded by double quotes'
